          <avActivityHighlights>The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust only at high altitudes and will soften during the day. Faceted weak layers exist in the bottom section of the snowpack on steep shady slopes.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>The avalanche prone locations for dry avalanches are to be found on steep shady slopes above approximately 2800 m. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of warming during the day and the solar radiation, the likelihood of wet avalanches being released will increase in particular on steep shady slopes below approximately 2800 m. &lt;br/&gt; Medium-sized avalanches are possible.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>The surface of the snowpack will soften during the day. &lt;br/&gt; Steep shady slopes above approximately 2800 m: Faceted weak layers exist in the bottom section of the old snowpack. &lt;br/&gt; Below approximately 2100 m from a snow sport perspective, in most cases insufficient snow is lying.</snowpackStructureComment>
